The first thing my doctor said to me when I was diagnosed with ovarian cancer is “I don’t care who it is, get negative people out of your life so that you can heal!” He said that staying positive and keeping a sense of humor was as important to my recovery as surgery and chemotherapy.  Humor has always been my coping skill and I truly feel that finding the funny in my circumstances, and BELIEVING that everything would be okay, helped me heal.  Everybody has something, and I hope that you can find the humor in whatever you are going through.

Many of my life lessons have come on the basketball court. My high school coach, Jim Smiddy, is in the Women’s Basketball Hall of Fame and is one of the winningest coaches in history on any level. Coach Smiddy was very much a role-player type of coach.  I was the point guard and my role was to feed the ball to Data, our 6’2” center. I rarely ever shot in a game (because that wasn’t my job), but Coach Smiddy would make me stay after school every day and MAKE 250 shots before I could go home. I couldn’t understand why I had to stay and shoot. That question was answered in the finals of the state championship in 1976, 3 seconds left on the clock, we were down by 1…

It’s a lesson I have always carried with me…be prepared because you never know when it will be your moment to shine.

Thanks to all of the folks who came out to my shows this past weekend.  Such fun crowds, and many people drove hours to attend.  I could not be more grateful! ❤️ 

The Plaza Arts Center in Eatonton, GA ROCKED! What an awesome venue...and a special shout out to Mary Ann who drove from Knoxville and brought her little dachshund, Rona. Rona made my night, even though she didn't want me smooching on her while she was trying to play with her toy. 😘 🐶 😂 

The Tybee Post Theatre was adorable!  I wish I could have spent a little extra time on Tybee Island but hopefully next time! It was a sold out show and when I did the bit about losing my car in the parking lot, one fan ran up and brought me a "car finder" he had made. 🪠 😂 

The Historic Ritz Theater in Toccoa, Ga was fantastic!  Another great little theater that was intimate and so fun to play. The audience was wonderful, and shout out to the group of animal rescuers on the front row.  Thank you for what you do! 

@theplazaartscenter @tybeepost @historic_ritz_theatre_toccoa thank you so much for having me!

And, a very special thank you to all the talented comics who opened for me - you all did a great job! 👏 👏 👏 @tarabrowncomedy @kingjasonallen @j.j_mcpherson

September is ovarian cancer awareness month. 

It’s been 10 years since I was diagnosed with OC and I want to say a big thank you to my family, friends, doctors, nurses, and dogs who helped me through it, and continue to support my journey to live a healthy life. My doctor told me when I was diagnosed to get negative people out of my life so that I could heal.  He said that having a good attitude and a positive outlook was as important to my recovery as surgery and chemotherapy. 

Whether it is cancer or any other of life’s challenges, always try to keep your sense of humor and surround yourself with people who lift you up.  It really can be a matter of life or death!
